  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering penalties can include significant fines and prison sentences. Typically, penalties depend on the specific circumstances of the offense, such as the amount of money involved and whether it's a first or repeat offense. Generally, money laundering can result in:\n\n1. Prison Sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison\n- Potentially longer sentences for more serious cases\n- Consecutive sentences possible for multiple counts\n\n2. Financial Penalties:\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n- Potential asset forfeiture\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n\nThe specific penalties are typically determined by statutes like 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957, which outline federal money laundering offenses. Factors like intent, transaction amount, and involvement in other criminal activities can influence the severity of penalties.\n\nFor precise details about a specific situation, it's advisable to consult with a qualified legal professional who specializes in federal criminal law.",
